This includes very large and heavy components, usually cylindrical. So they have                  to be prepared in parts and then assembled later. They are joined together with help of welding, namely Long-seam welding (along the length) and circular-seam welding (along the circumference). Thus welding becomes a most important and critical process for manufacturing large components, their strength, efficiency, and durability. And hence the weld inspection also becomes an important aspect of production.

This is done by non – destructive testing like ultra-sonic testing which requires the ultrasound to pass through the weld. Doing it manually is a difficult task, limited maneuverability, risk of accidents errors in inspection etc. Here, the adhesion – locomotive system comes into picture. It can travel over the job carrying all the equipments required for testing without falling down due its weight.

- **RESEARCH**

**      ****3.1**** ****Halbach array**

**          **

The main crux in the adhesion – locomotive system is the strength of the magnetic wheel. This project aims at providing the maximum possible force for the given size of the wheel. The strength of the magnetic wheel mostly depends on the arrangement of magnets within it, such that they add up to their original magnetic field.

Such a type of strong arrangement is the Halbach array. A Halbach array is a special arrangement of permanent magnets that makes the magnetic field on one side of the array stronger, while canceling the field to near zero on the other side.  This is very different from the magnetic field around a single magnet. The advantages of one-sided flux distributions are twofold:

- The field is twice as large on the side on which the flux is confined (in the idealized case).

- There is no stray field produced (in the ideal case) on the opposite side. This helps with field confinement, usually a problem in the design of magnetic structures.

                                                                Normal Array                                   Halbach Array

The above figure represents a linear Halbach array. But the similar type of analogy can be used in circular form. But this opens door for few variety of orientations in the circular array which may affect location of strong and weak side and also the magnitude of the magnetic field density on stronger side.

	**3.2 ****Halbach Cylinder**

A Halbach cylinder is a magnetized cylinder which produces a intense magnetic field on inner side of the cylinder and almost zero on the outer side of the cylinder. The cylinder can also be magnetized in such a way that it produces a stronger magnetic field on the outer diameter of the cylinder and a weak magnetic field over the inner diameter of the cylinder.

The different orientations are denoted by letter p which may have values p = +1, -1, +2, -2, +3, -3. Where the negative and positive sign indicates the presence of strong magnetic field over outer diameter or the inner diameter respectively. And the magnitude of the number represents the number of poles of the Halbach Cylinder. For example, 1 represents Di – polar array, 2 represents Quadro – polar array, and 3 represents Hexa – polar array. 

For the application of Halbach Cylinder in this project a, Halbach cylinder with negative value of p is considered. As the outer surface of the cylinder will be in contact with the ferromagnetic surface there is requirement of stronger field on the outer surface of the wheel.

**3.3**** ****Prototype Testing**

The testing procedures clearly indicate that the pull force (𝐹t) is applied though a digital force gauge against the measurement force, where (𝐹a) is wheel adhesion and (f) is wheel friction force. The magnetic wheel tyre is connected by hook arrangement to the digital force gauge of motorized test stand for the adhesion force measurements and the pull force is applied though motorized test stand with linear actuator against the measurement force. Wheel mechanism is linked to a digital force gauge using hooks and non-stretchable steel wire rope for coefficient of friction measurement. The digital force gauge mounted on motorized test stand pulls in case of adhesion force testing and slides in case of COF testing the magnetic wheel with some speed.

  

- ** CALCULATIONS**

**4.1 Magnetic Field calculations**

Under the calculations the project aims at finding the resultant magnetic field due to the Halbach cylinder and the corresponding pull force applied on the ferromagnetic surface. Firstly, few properties of magnetic material need to be defined – Remanent magnetic field, magnetic permeability, and relative permeability.

The calculations begin with relating the magnetic flux density (B) to the magnetic vector potential (A). And then defining the Magnetic vector potential.

B = ∇×A 

Boundary Conditions

The constants are calculated with help of boundary conditions. And then the radial and circumferential magnetic flux density (B) is calculated with help of relation with magnetic vector potential as given below.

But the above calculations shown calculate the magnetic field density at particular point are due to an ideal Halbach Cylinder which has a homogeneous and continuous magnetic field, and which is difficult to construct for practical use. In practical the Halbach cylinder is constructed using discrete magnets of identical size which generate similar field.

   

                                    Homogeneous Array             Discrete Array

		

The discretization of Halbach Cylinder lower its magnetic field and hence its pulling force. Thus it is necessary to take into consideration the discrete nature of Halbach array. NMR Mandhalas (Magnetic Arrangement for Novel Discrete Halbach Layout) defines the ratio by which the magnetic field of a discrete Halbach cylinder reduce by. 

Since ideal Halbach cylinders (infinitely long cylinders of continuously changing magnetization direction) cannot be produced, they are usually made in a discretized fashion of the ideal one. NMR-Mandhalas are simply discrete versions which can be built from a single magnet type (one shape, one magnetization direction). Thus the field due to discrete Halbach array is given by multiplying the magnetic field due to ideal Halbach cylinder with the ratio of the area of the block magnets to that of a Halbach cylinder.  

