		- **DESIGN**

	- **Halbach Cylinder**

During the designing of magnetic wheel, the following parameters were taken into consideration.

- Pitch circle diameter of the wheel.

- Size of the block magnet.

- Number of magnets in the cylinder.

- Inner and outer diameter of Halbach cylinder.

The most important aspect during the designing of the Halbach cylinder is the roll angle i.e. the angle through which the direction of magnetic orientation of the next magnet change w.r.t the magnet preceding it. This gives rise to mainly two types of Halbach cylinder design.

	- Quadro-polar Halbach Cylinder ( p = -2)

	- Hexa-polar Halbach Cylinder (p = -3)

The Quadro-polar array generates four poles within the Halbach cylinder and the Hexa-polar array generates six poles on the Halbach cylinder as shown in figure below. 

Hence the basic design for both Quadro-polar and hexa-polar was generated using the Solid Edge software along with the orientation of the magnetic poles as shown below.

              

   Quadro-polar Halbach Cylinder     Hexa-polar Halbach Cylinder

- **Wheel Prototype**

Along with the basic design for the Halbach cylinder the prototype wheel assembly was also designed on Solid Edge CAD modeling software to carry out static and dynamic tests. The design consists of the outer and inner sleeves to cover the Halbach cylinder and a shaft with keyway that would drive the wheel. The exploded view of the same is shown below.

	-  **Static Test**** Setup**

	The static test setup consists of a magnetic wheel which is attached to a ferromagnetic surface. A rod is then inserted in the central portion of wheel in a horizontal manner such that its both ends extend out of the width of the wheel. Then an inelastic string is tied to both ends of the rod in such way that it forms a hook. Then another string is attached to the hook which passes over a pulley vertically above it then over a pulley at the same elevation. This string is then pulled downwards by adding weights gradually. 

	

	

	

	

	-  **Dynamic Test**** Setup**

	

	The dynamic test setup consists of two slides. One slide in horizontal direction and other in vertical direction perpendicular to the first one. Carriages are placed on the slides so that they can move free in one particular diection. The slides are connected by a plate using fasteners. On the carriage of vertical slide a C – Bracket is mounted such that one of the face of C – Bracket is threaded on to the face of carriage and a DC motor is mounted on the opposite face of the bracket. Between the walls of C – Bracket a shaft with wheel is mounted on bearings such that it can rotate freely over the shaft of the motor. The lower surface of the horizontal slide is made up of mild steel so that the wheel sticks to it and moves horizontally along the slide. Simultaneously weights are added to the wheel, once it reaches its maximum limit the wheel ditaches and moves along the vertical slide.

	

	

